## Performance Review — `TimeSpanFormatting.cs`

### 🔴 Critical

#### 1. LINQ allocation storm on every `Humanize()` call (8 sites)

**Impact:** 8–12 enumerator/delegate/list allocations per call, devastating at millions of calls/min.
**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L128, L140, L143, L146, L149, L158, L169, L284`
**Fix:** Replace LINQ chains with `foreach` loops over `List<string?>` directly. The full call chain creates:
- `IsContainingOnlyNullValue` → `.Any()` allocates enumerator + delegate (L128)
- `SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan` → up to 3 LINQ wrappers (`.Where`, `.Take`, `.Where`) + `[.. timeParts]` materialization (L140–149)
- `ConcatenateTimeSpanParts` → `.Where().ToList()` yet another list (L158)
- `parts.Take(count - 1)` → enumerator just to skip last element (L169)

```csharp
// Before (L127-128)
private static bool IsContainingOnlyNullValue(IEnumerable<string?> timeParts) =>
    !timeParts.Any(x => x != null);

// After
private static bool IsContainingOnlyNullValue(List<string?> timeParts)
{
    foreach (var part in timeParts)
        if (part != null) return false;
    return true;
}
```

```csharp
// Before (L133-149) — SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan
private static List<string?> SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan(
    IEnumerable<string?> timeParts, int precision, bool countEmptyUnits)
{
    if (!countEmptyUnits)
        timeParts = timeParts.Where(x => x != null);
    timeParts = timeParts.Take(precision);
    if (countEmptyUnits)
        timeParts = timeParts.Where(x => x != null);
    return [.. timeParts];
}

// After — single pass, zero LINQ
private static List<string?> SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan(
    List<string?> timeParts, int precision, bool countEmptyUnits)
{
    var result = new List<string?>(precision);
    int taken = 0;
    foreach (var part in timeParts)
    {
        if (taken >= precision) break;
        if (countEmptyUnits) taken++;
        if (part != null)
        {
            if (!countEmptyUnits) taken++;
            result.Add(part);
        }
    }
    return result;
}
```

```csharp
// Before (L155-170) — ConcatenateTimeSpanParts
var parts = timeSpanParts.Where(x => x != null).ToList();
...
var allButLast = string.Join(collectionSeparator, parts.Take(parts.Count - 1));

// After — accept List, use range overload
private static string ConcatenateTimeSpanParts(
    List<string?> timeSpanParts, CultureInfo culture, string collectionSeparator)
{
    // timeSpanParts already filtered to non-null by SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan
    if (timeSpanParts.Count == 0) return "no time";
    if (timeSpanParts.Count == 1) return timeSpanParts[0]!;
    var allButLast = string.Join(collectionSeparator,
        timeSpanParts.GetRange(0, timeSpanParts.Count - 1));
    return $"{allButLast} and {timeSpanParts[^1]}";
}
```

#### 2. `FormatTimePart` allocates 3 strings per unit — compound allocation (1 site)

**Impact:** `enum.ToString()` + `.ToLowerInvariant()` + interpolation = 3 heap allocations per time part, called up to 8× per `Humanize()`.
**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L174-176`
**Fix:** Pre-cache unit name strings in a static array indexed by `TimeUnit`. Only 8 enum values exist.

```csharp
// Before
private static string FormatTimePart(int value, TimeUnit unit, CultureInfo culture)
{
    var unitName = unit.ToString().ToLowerInvariant();
    return value == 1 ? $"{value} {unitName}" : $"{value} {unitName}s";
}

// After — pre-cached names, eliminates 2 of 3 allocations per call
private static readonly string[] s_unitNames =
    ["millisecond", "second", "minute", "hour", "day", "week", "month", "year"];
private static readonly string[] s_unitNamesPlural =
    ["milliseconds", "seconds", "minutes", "hours", "days", "weeks", "months", "years"];

private static string FormatTimePart(int value, TimeUnit unit, CultureInfo culture)
{
    int index = (int)unit;
    // Reverse index because TimeUnit enum is ordered largest-first
    int i = s_unitNames.Length - 1 - index;
    string name = value == 1 ? s_unitNames[i] : s_unitNamesPlural[i];
    return $"{value} {name}";
}
```
**Caveat:** Pre-cached names assume English-only. If localization is needed, use a per-culture cache.

